From the censure which it frequently passes upon the corruption and degen- eracy of the times it has been considered as a mere satire upon Ro· man manners, in the age of Tacitus. But to say nothing of the ill adaptation of the whole plan to a satirical work, there are large parts of the treatise, which must have been prepared with great la- bor, and yet can have no possible bearing on such a design. Satires are not wont to abound in historica] notices and geographica] details, especially touching a foreign and distant land.
